<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Royal Town Planning Institute</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Royal Town Planning Institute (RTPI) is please</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to respond to the call for written evidence to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Environmental Audit Committee Inquiry to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">examine the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Code for Sustainable Homes and the Housing Standards Review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The RTPI is the largest professional institute for planners in Europe, representing some 23,000 spatial planners. The Institute seeks to advance the science and art of spatial planning for the benefit of the public. As well as promoting spatial planning, the RTPI develops and shapes policy affecting the built environment, works to raise professional standards and supports members through continuous education, training and development.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The views in this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">submission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> follow consultation with the members of the RTPI, and specifically the members of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">English Policy Panel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Panel has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">varied membership with experts in the full range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">planning policy fields</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> represented.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">General Position</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support the simplification and rationalisation of standards – the Taylor Review of Planning Guidance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">show</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> what can be achieved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the potential benefits. However,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if the objective of clarity is to be delivered, rather than additional confusion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from poorly focused and uncoordinated change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the RTPI believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more work is required.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A good indication of the additional work required is given by the Challenge Panel in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Towards more Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The RTPI believes that the Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should set down a clear, timetabled and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> plan for housing standards, in particular showing how the ‘zero carbon by 2016’ commitment is to be delivered by all parties and showing which elements of the Code for Sustainable Homes are being dropped – if any. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National Planning Policy Framework (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NPPF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> including a ‘presumption in favour of sustainable development’ it would seem </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a perverse and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">retrograde to act </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in any way </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to compromise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sustainability objectives.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Role of the Building Regulations</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is the RTPI’s view that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should move immediately to update and amend the Building Regulations rather than ask that, generally overstretched and under-resourced, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Planning Authorities (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LPAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should institute Local Plan reviews to justify and incorporate standards as a merely interim measure. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is inevitable that LPA positions on standards will be even less predictable in this interim period whereas builders broadly know where they stand at the present. It is notable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and concerning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that the public sector costs of implementing two changes – through Local Plans and then the Building Regula</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tions – have not been assessed.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the review process for updating and incorporating additions to the Building Regulations is not fit for purpose </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is too slow and/or unwieldy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as is implied by the Review document</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, then this deficiency must be addressed to provide the assurance required by local authorities who will be foregoing the potential to innovate with standards as changed expectations are identified.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Eco-friendly Standards</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The RTPI is concerned that too little attention has been given to the potential for higher standards to be justified and marketed on the basis of the significant user savings achievable. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In particular there is potential for lenders to incorporate more explicitly the savings as an incentive mechanism into their loan-to-income evaluations for lending.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4. Setting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Standards</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is noted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Impact Assessment that, “Based on discussions with local authorities and other partners, we have estimated that around 90% of new homes in London are built to the Lifetime Homes standard and 5% outside of London”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This seems to indicate that where ‘headroom’ exists in the pricing of housing, so-called </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standards are adopted and welcomed. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it would a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ppear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that we are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> entering another period of increasing house prices, to be matched by increases in supply, it is all the more important that the pathway to raising standards to an equal level across England is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set out now and mechanisms set in motion.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>